<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-152-356  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 152 356.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  March 2 1989 v15 n5 p35(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Monitoring and system diagnosis the wave of the future.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Janz, Al.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Improved computer technology has led to changes in the serviceindustry as users become more dependent on their computers andproblems become more difficult to isolate.andP;  Service vendors mustfind new ways to maintain system availability and eliminate asmuch as possible costly downtime.andP;  On-site support must becomplemented by fast, powerful and sophisticated tools using thelatest technology and most effective methods.andP;  Service providersmust be able to respond immediately to service calls, diagnoseproblems instantly and make correct maintenance decisions withinminutes.andP;  Service providers are developing new kinds of monitoringand diagnostic tools in response to this need.andP;  The tools cananalyze errors, predict potential failures, follow the action onany node and warn the system operator of trouble on the system ornetwork before it occurs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Support ServicesMaintenanceService IndustryIndustry AnalysisDiagnosticsNetwork ManagementOn-Site.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>